    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1968-01-22T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1968-01-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="378"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d378">
                <head>378. Memorandum From the Presidentʼs Special Assistant (<persName
                        corresp="#p_RWW1" type="from">Rostow</persName>) to Secretary of State
                        <persName corresp="#p_RD1" type="to">Rusk</persName> and Secretary of
                    Defense <persName corresp="#p_MNRS1">McNamara</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d378fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, DEF 6 THAI. Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1968-01-22">January 22, 1968</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Thai Troops for Viet Nam</item>
                </list>
                <p>The President accepts the case made in your recent memoranda<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d378fn2">
                        <ref target="#d375">Documents 375</ref> and <ref target="#d377"
                        >377</ref>.</note> on the indicated subject that only combat-ready Thai
                    forces be sent to Viet Nam.</p>
                <p>It remains his objective, however, that the arrival in Viet Nam of the first
                    additional Thai contingent be at the earliest possible date.</p>
                <p>To this end he wishes to be assured: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>That we are providing training equipment to Thailand on an accelerated
                            schedule, so that there is no possibility whatsoever that equipment
                            shortage could be a cause or an excuse for delay.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>That we have exhausted every possibility of inducing the Thais to send
                            a unit of men already trained for combat.</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>That we have set, in any case, clear target dates for the dispatch of
                            these forces, firmly understood between ourselves and the Thais.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RWW1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Walt</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
